1
00:00:05,310 --> 00:00:09,540
You're probably familiar with one other plot type that is used for

2
00:00:09,540 --> 00:00:14,175
plotting relative frequencies for qualitative variables, the pie chart.

3
00:00:14,175 --> 00:00:17,800
In a pie chart, each category is indicated by a slice of

4
00:00:17,800 --> 00:00:22,805
a circle with the area indicating the relative frequency of that category.

5
00:00:22,805 --> 00:00:25,855
A variant of the pie chart, the donut plot,

6
00:00:25,855 --> 00:00:31,380
is very similar except that the center of the circle has been removed, leaving a donut.

7
00:00:31,380 --> 00:00:37,500
Most of the time, you'll probably prefer a bar chart over either on these two plots.

8
00:00:37,500 --> 00:00:41,040
It is actually fairly difficult to get an accurate estimate of

9
00:00:41,040 --> 00:00:44,835
relative frequency from a pie or donut plot alone.

10
00:00:44,835 --> 00:00:47,060
If there are a lot of categories,

11
00:00:47,060 --> 00:00:52,575
there are major limitations on how many categories can be plotted in a readable way.

12
00:00:52,575 --> 00:00:56,020
A bar chart will usually be more versatile and should be

13
00:00:56,020 --> 00:00:59,269
your first choice for exploring qualitative variables.

14
00:00:59,269 --> 00:01:03,520
That's not to say that pie or donut charts should never be used however.

15
00:01:03,520 --> 00:01:06,035
If you want to use one of these charts,

16
00:01:06,035 --> 00:01:08,820
then you should keep in mind a few guidelines.

17
00:01:08,820 --> 00:01:12,170
First of all, you only want to use a pie chart if you want to

18
00:01:12,170 --> 00:01:15,735
show how the whole of the data is broken down into parts.

19
00:01:15,735 --> 00:01:20,320
Second, you should plan on only plotting a small number of slices.

20
00:01:20,320 --> 00:01:23,580
A pie chart works best with two or three slices,

21
00:01:23,580 --> 00:01:26,860
so that the relative portions are distinct.

22
00:01:26,860 --> 00:01:30,645
If you determine that a pie chart meet these two criteria,

23
00:01:30,645 --> 00:01:35,575
you should then organize your plot to clearly convey the information in your data.

24
00:01:35,575 --> 00:01:38,915
Usually, you should start planning from the 12 o'clock position and

25
00:01:38,915 --> 00:01:42,690
then mark slices clockwise in order of frequency.

26
00:01:42,690 --> 00:01:46,125
There are other reasonable ways of generating a pie chart,

27
00:01:46,125 --> 00:01:48,970
but you should consider your data carefully about both

28
00:01:48,970 --> 00:01:53,200
whether you should use a pie chart and how best to present it.

